## 3. Principles of Environmental Science

These are the foundational ideas that guide the entire field. Learn them as distinct, testable statements:

**Principle 1 — Interdependence / Interconnectedness**
All components of the environment (biotic and abiotic) are interrelated. A change in one component affects others. Example: cutting forests affects rainfall, which affects soil, which affects biodiversity.

**Principle 2 — Carrying Capacity**
Every ecosystem has a finite capacity to support life. Exceeding this leads to degradation. This principle directly links to population ecology (Unit 3.9).

**Principle 3 — Sustainability / Sustainable Development**
Meeting the needs of the present without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs (Brundtland Commission, 1987 — Our Common Future). UGC NET frequently asks the source of this definition.

**Principle 4 — Precautionary Principle**
When an action raises threats to the environment or human health, precautionary measures should be taken even if some cause-and-effect relationships are not fully established scientifically. This principle is embedded in several international conventions.

**Principle 5 — Polluter Pays Principle (PPP)**
The party responsible for producing pollution is responsible for paying for the damage done. This is legally codified in Indian environmental law.

**Principle 6 — Principle of Entropy (linked to thermodynamics)**
Energy degrades in quality with each transformation. High-quality energy (sunlight) → used → low-quality heat. Connects directly to Unit 1.3.

**Principle 7 — Conservation of Matter**
Matter is neither created nor destroyed, only transformed. Pollutants don't disappear — they cycle and accumulate. This underpins bioaccumulation and biomagnification concepts.

**Principle 8 — Nature Knows Best / Gaia Hypothesis**
Natural systems have evolved over billions of years and are inherently balanced. Human interference disrupts these balances. The Gaia Hypothesis (James Lovelock) views Earth as a self-regulating system.

